You're most likely missing the `BindingContext`. The XAML bindings have nothing to resolve against.

**Fix — set the `BindingContext` in code-behind:**

```csharp
public partial class MyPage : ContentPage
{
    public MyPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
    }
}
```

**Also ensure your ViewModel implements `INotifyPropertyChanged`** (or inherits `ObservableObject` from the MVVM Toolkit) so the UI updates when properties change:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _title;
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; OnPropertyChanged(); }
    }
    // ... same for Description

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler PropertyChanged;
    void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string name = null)
        => PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(name));
}
```

**TL;DR** — No `BindingContext` = no data. Bindings silently fail when there's nothing to bind to.
